\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Entrepreneurship is often treated as a driver of innovation,
 productivity,
 and growth.
 However,
 not all entrepreneurship has the same economic role.
 In many settings,
 a substantial share of entry is necessity-driven rather than opportunity-driven.
 This distinction matters because necessity entry can reflect weak labor-market outside options rather than comparative advantage in managing production.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Empirical work typically separates necessity and opportunity entrepreneurship using survey responses or prior labor-market status.
 Both approaches are useful,
 but each has limits.
 Self-reported motives are subjective,
 while classifications based only on previous employment status can misclassify agents whose timing is strategic or constrained by insurance and search frictions.
 A worker who expects separation may enter early and look 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

opportunity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the data;
 an unemployed household can enter temporarily while searching and look 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

necessity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 even when underlying talent is high.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper provides a model-based definition that maps directly into counterfactual behavior.
 We define opportunity entrepreneurs as households that choose entrepreneurship regardless of whether they enter the period employed or non-employed.
 We define necessity entrepreneurs as households that choose entrepreneurship only when they lack an employment relationship.
 The model combines heterogeneous managerial talent,
 human-capital heterogeneity,
 search frictions,
 and social insurance,
 allowing us to quantify how labor-market risk and policy jointly shape the composition of entrepreneurship.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our contribution is threefold.
 First,
 we provide a structural framework in which necessity entrepreneurship emerges endogenously from occupational choice under incomplete insurance.
 Second,
 we provide a quantitative decomposition of how unemployment risk and unemployment insurance affect entry margins and firm scale across education groups.
 Third,
 we reinterpret necessity entry as a misallocation channel:
 low outside options can push households into entrepreneurship even when their productivity is better used in paid work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of the paper proceeds as follows.
 Section 2 discusses related literature.
 Section 3 presents the economic environment.
 Section 4 characterizes household behavior and equilibrium.
 Section 5 discusses calibration.
 Section 6 presents baseline quantitative results.
 Section 7 studies policy counterfactuals,
 and Section 8 concludes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Literature Review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper connects three strands in a single quantitative framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First,
 we build on work that separates opportunity and necessity entrepreneurship in the data.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fairlie_fossen_2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 propose an operational distinction based on pre-entry labor market status and show that opportunity and necessity entrepreneurship have different cyclical patterns.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sedlacek_sterk_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that startup cohorts differ in growth potential across the business cycle.
 This maps directly to our decomposition of entrepreneurial entry by prior employment state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second,
 we connect to the entrepreneurship-and-frictions literature.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "buera_2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 shows in a dynamic model that borrowing constraints can materially change both entry and firm scale,
 with large welfare effects through undercapitalized businesses.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hurst_pugsley_2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 documents that many small businesses are not primarily innovation-driven and that nonpecuniary motives are quantitatively important.
 This evidence supports modeling entrepreneurship as a broad occupational margin rather than only a high-innovation margin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third,
 our labor-market block follows the search-and-matching tradition.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "petrongolo_pissarides_2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provides the aggregate matching-function synthesis that motivates our use of separation and job-finding transitions to discipline occupational flows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relative to these strands,
 our contribution is to embed an explicit opportunity-versus-necessity distinction in a heterogeneous-agent model with search frictions,
 incomplete insurance,
 and policy counterfactuals.
 This structure lets us quantify how unemployment risk and social insurance jointly shift entrepreneurial entry,
 firm scale,
 and composition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Model:
 Economic Environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a Lucas (1978) span of control model,
 where individuals differ in the level of human capital,
 
\begin_inset Formula $h.$
\end_inset

 As in Gomez and Kuhen (2017),
 individuals are educated to either the primary 
\begin_inset Formula $(P)$
\end_inset

,
 secondary 
\begin_inset Formula $(S)$
\end_inset

 or tertiary level 
\begin_inset Formula $(T)$
\end_inset

.
 The level of education means that a tertiary educated individuals have a higher draw of human capital,
 on average,
 than secondary educated individuals,
 who in turn have a higher draw on average than primary educated individuals.
 This human capital draw is positively correlated with managerial ability 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as well as labor productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the start of the period agents enter as either unemployed 
\begin_inset Formula $($
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=0)$
\end_inset

,
 employed 
\begin_inset Formula $($
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=1)$
\end_inset

,
 or an entrepreneur 
\begin_inset Formula $($
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=2)$
\end_inset

.
 Individuals face a choice of whether to become an entrepreneur,
 to continue working or to search for work.
 However,
 the value of employment is different depending on whether an agent enters the period as employed 
\begin_inset Formula $($
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=1)$
\end_inset

 or not.
 Although there is a risk that an employee may become separated from a firm with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

,
 this is less risky than searching for work which has a 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\theta)$
\end_inset

 probability of obtaining employment.
 Consequently,
 the expected value of employment is higher for those already in employment than those who are not.
 Additionally,
 the probability of separation is lower for individuals with higher levels of human capital and they are able to command a higher wage due to higher levels of productivity.
 So the value of employment,
 holding other things equal,
 is higher for those with higher human capital as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The innovation of this model is that the entrepreneurial decision results in two types of entrepreneurs emerge,
 opportunity-based entrepreneurs and necessity-based entrepreneurs.
 We define opportunity-based entrepreneurs are those whose value of entrepreneurship is higher,
 even if they had employment.
 Necessity-based entrepreneurs are those who would not have become entrepreneurs,
 if they had employment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Timing:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of events can be summarized below.
 Occupational choice happens at the start of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t.$
\end_inset

 Those choosing to become entrepreneurs run projects and hire workers on on rolling contracts (i.e.
 contracts,
 will be reassessed each period).
 Those who were previously employed within a project can decide to carry on working but carry a risk of separation with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 If separation occurs these workers will claim unemployed benefits and be unable to look for work until the following period.
 After separation occurs,
 vacancies are posted and who were unemployed in the previous period are matched with firms.
 Those that are successful and match with with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\theta)$
\end_inset

 go on to earn a wage.
 Whereas those that are unsuccessful will claim unemployment benefits and be unable to search again until the following period.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the search and matching literature there is no wage bargaining between workers and the firm at the end of matching.
 Instead the wage pins down the occupational choice decision which determines those wanting to become entrepreneurs and those who will search for work.
 Crucially,
 the worker only finds out whether they enter production and earn a wage after their occupational choice decision.
\end_layout

