\begin_layout Subsection
Preferences,
 endowments and technology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Preferences:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consumption by an agent in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 with utility given by 
\begin_inset Formula $U(c_{t})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Endowments:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Agents are endowed with an initial capital asset,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 which can be used as an input in production.
 Each individual is endowed with human capital shock 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Human capital 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is positively correlated with managerial talent 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 labor productivity 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and separation rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Production:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firms use labor 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and capital 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to produce a single consumption good,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Capital depreciates at a constant rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 Managers can operate only one project.
 The functional form of the production function is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=xk^{\alpha}(zn){}^{\gamma}\ \ \mbox{where}\ \alpha,\gamma>0.\ \label{eq:firm_prod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Managerial talent 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is determined by the Pareto distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)=\left[1+\frac{x-\varsigma}{\xi}\right]^{-\vartheta_{i}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta$
\end_inset

 is the shape parameter,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma$
\end_inset

 the location parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is the scale parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Factor remuneration:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firms rent capital at the common market rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Government:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government runs a balanced budget each period and provides unemployment insurance which is financed through lump sum taxation 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

,
 which is shared by the employee 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\psi)\tau$
\end_inset

 and employer 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\tau$
\end_inset

.
 This program guarantees each household an unemployment benefit of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Firm's problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The firm's problem is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{n,k}Xk^{\alpha}n^{\gamma}-(1+\tau\psi)wzn-rk-\kappa\frac{\rho zn}{q(\theta_{t})}\label{eq:max_firm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

employees must pay a share of unemployment insurance 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to all workers who produce output.
 Firms have to pay search costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 for all vacancies posted.
 The number of vacancies posted is designed to replace any lost workers,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho zn.$
\end_inset

 This,
 however,
 is affected by the firm-hiring rate 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\theta_{t})=\bar{m}\left(\frac{v_{t}}{u_{t}}\right)^{-\mu}$
\end_inset

,
 where aggregate vacancies 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 is simply the aggregate level of all those who have separate from firms 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\rho zn$
\end_inset

 within the period and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the total unemployed looking for work within that period (see appendix).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the market is tight and the hiring rate is low,
 firms have to search more and thus face higher search costs in order to replace lost workers.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{This is because }0<q(\theta_{t})<1,$
\end_inset

so a lower 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\theta_{t})$
\end_inset

 increases 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\rho zn}{q(\theta_{t})}$
\end_inset

.
 If the firm lose 10 workers,
 they want to hire 10 workers to replace them.
 But if the hiring rate,
 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\theta_{t}),$
\end_inset

 is 50% then they will face double the amount of search costs than if 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\theta_{t})$
\end_inset

 were 100%.
 The upshot of this is that when markets are tight,
 the size of the desired firm size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 decreases ex ante ,
 as the cost of replacing workers is high and so entrepreneurs would prefer to run smaller firms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To avoid issues of directed search,
 we assume that employees are randomly matched with firms (as in Chivers et al.,
 2015) and each firm employees a distribution of workers across the human capital spectrum such that each firm employs the market average.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Optimal behavior and equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 agents are distinguished by 
\begin_inset Formula $(h,a,x,i,z)$
\end_inset

.
 The timing of the economy is given as follows.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Households enter each new period with assets 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and an employment status 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Idiosyncratic shocks 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is drawn which determines 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (managerial ability) and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 (labor productivity),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 seperation rate conditional on education level,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P,S$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $T.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Households make an occupation decision:
 entrepreneur (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{e}=1$
\end_inset

) or worker (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{e}=0$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Capital and labor markets clear.
 A fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 of employees separate from firms and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $p(\theta)$
\end_inset

 are hired to replace them 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Households choose:
 consumption (
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

),
 borrowing/saving (
\begin_inset Formula $a'$
\end_inset

) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Firm manager
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firms are distinguished by their productivity realization 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Agents with sufficient ability to become managers choose the level of capital and the number of employees to maximize profit subject to a technological constraint.
 In order to simplify the exposition,
 first consider the problem of a manager with talent 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{i}$
\end_inset

 for a given level of capital 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (i.e.,
 labor input choice only):
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{zn}xk^{\alpha}(zn){}^{\gamma}-zw(1+\psi\tau)n-rk-\kappa\frac{\rho zn}{q(\theta)}\label{maxP}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first order conditions are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma xk^{\alpha}(zn)^{\gamma-1}=w(1+\psi\tau)+\frac{\rho\kappa}{q(\theta)}\label{maxP-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
n^{*}(k,x,\widetilde{w})=\left[\frac{\gamma xk^{\alpha}}{w(1+\psi\tau)+\frac{\rho\kappa}{q(\theta)}}\right]^{\frac{1}{1-\gamma}}\label{FOC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "FOC"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "maxP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

) yields the manager's profit function for a given level of capital:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y(k,x,\widetilde{w})=xk^{\alpha}(zn^{*})^{\gamma}-zn^{*}w(1+\psi\tau)-\kappa\frac{\rho zn^{*}}{q(\theta)}\label{profitj}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Initially we assume capital markets function perfectly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Entrepreneurs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Entrepreneurs maximize expected discounted utility of consumption 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\{c_{t},a_{t+1}\}}\mathbb{E}\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{t}U(c_{t})
\]

\end_inset

subject to the following budget constraint:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c+a' & \leq(1+r-\delta)a+\nu-\tau_{\pi}\label{eq:c_worker-3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a'\geq-\bar{a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Employed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The workforce (previous periods employed who choose to reapply for work) maximize expected discounted utility of consumption 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\{c_{t},a_{t+1}\}}\mathbb{E}\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{t}U(c_{t})
\]

\end_inset

subject to the following budget constraint:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c+a' & \leq(1+r-\delta)a+(1-\rho)\left(wz(1-(1-\psi)\tau_{y})\right)+\rho b\label{eq:c_worker}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a'\geq-\bar{a}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the unemployment benefit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unemployed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unemployed maximize expected discounted utility of consumption 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\{c_{t},a_{t+1}\}}\mathbb{E}\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\beta^{t}U(c_{t})
\]

\end_inset

subject to the following budget constraint:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c+a' & \leq(1+r-\delta)a+p(\theta)\left(wz(1-(1-\psi)\tau_{y})\right)+(1-p(\theta))b\label{eq:c_worker-2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a'\geq-\bar{a}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the unemployment benefit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Government 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government runs a balanced budget with a lump-sum taxes 
\begin_inset Formula $T(y)=(y-\lambda_{p}y^{1-\tau_{p}})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The household's problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}$
\end_inset

 denote the household's labor market status in the previous period,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=2$
\end_inset

 indicating being entrepreneur,
 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=1$
\end_inset

 being employed and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{w}=0$
\end_inset

 being unemployed.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{e}$
\end_inset

 indicate occupational choice,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{e}=1$
\end_inset

 if the household is an entrepreneur and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{e}=0$
\end_inset

 if the household is a worker.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 the expected value considering the possibility of being separated from the job as employed;
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}_{p(\theta)}$
\end_inset

 the expected value considering the possibility of finding new job if previously unmatched with a firm (unemployed former entrepreneurs).
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{w}$
\end_inset

 is the contemporary utility as a worker,
 which varies with the employment status.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota_{i_{w}=1}$
\end_inset

 is an indicator function.
 We can write the household's problem recursively as follows.
 More specifically,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{E}_{p(\theta)}\left(V_{w}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w})\right) & =p(\theta)\left(V_{n}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w}=1)\right)\\
 & +(1-p(\theta))\left(V_{u}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w}=0)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{E}_{\rho}\left(V_{w}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w})\right) & =\rho\left(V_{u}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w}=0)\right)\\
 & +(1-\rho)\left(V_{n}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w}=1)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Notice that for agents who recently separated from the firm cannot rematch with a new firm in the current period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{V}(a,h,i_{w}) & =\max_{\left\{ a',c,\mathcal{I}_{e}\right\} }\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
\iota_{i_{w}=0}\left[(1-\mathcal{I}_{e})\mathbb{E}_{p(\theta)}\left(V_{w}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w})\right)+\mathcal{I}_{e}\left(V_{e}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w}=0)\right)\right]+\\
\iota_{i_{w}=1}\left[(1-\mathcal{I}_{e})\mathbb{E}_{\rho}\left(V_{w}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w})\right)+\mathcal{I}_{e}\left(V_{e}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w}=0)\right)\right]+\\
\iota_{i_{w}=2}\left[(1-\mathcal{I}_{e})\mathbb{E}_{p(\theta)}\left(V_{w}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w})\right)+\mathcal{I}_{e}\left(V_{e}+\beta\mathbb{E}\mathbf{V}(a',x',i'_{w}=0)\right)\right]
\end{array}\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

subject to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c+a' & \leq(1-\tilde{{r}}-\delta)a+inc\label{eq:c_worker-1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
inc & =\begin{cases}
ra+\widetilde{w}_{n} & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{\mathcal{I}_{e}=0,} \ensuremath{i_{w}=1}}\\
ra+\widetilde{w}_{u} & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{\mathcal{I}_{e}=0,} \ensuremath{i_{w}\neq1}}\\
ra+\nu(k,x;\tilde{r},w,\tau) & \mbox{ if \ensuremath{\mathcal{I}_{e}=1}}
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $inc$
\end_inset

 is the earnings of the worker or entrepreneur,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{w}_{n}=(1-\rho)\left\{ zw(1-(1-\psi)\tau)\right\} +\rho b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{w}_{u}=p(\theta)\left\{ zw(1-(1-\psi)\tau)\right\} +\{1-p(\theta)\}b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}$
\end_inset

 be the critical value of human capital that determines occupational choice which is affected by both employment status and education level.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $h\geq\hat{h}$
\end_inset

 then individuals choose entrepreneurship over becoming a worker.
 The critical value of human capital is always higher for those who have employment than those who are unmatched with a firm 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}_{i_{w}\neq1}<\hat{h}_{i_{w}=1}$
\end_inset

.
 We define necessity entrepreneurship as those who would not have become an entrepreneur 
\shape italic
if
\shape default
 they had an employment contract:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{h}_{i_{w}\neq1}<h<\hat{h}_{i_{w}=1}.
\]

\end_inset

We define opportunity-driven entrepreneurship as those who would become an entrepreneur 
\shape italic
regardless
\shape default
 of circumstance:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\geq\hat{h}_{i_{w}=1}\geq\hat{h}_{i_{w}\neq1}
\]

\end_inset

As there are three education levels,
 there are a total of six critical values of human capital:
 two for primary educated matched or unmatched,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}_{i_{w}=1}^{P}\text{ and }\hat{h}_{i_{w}\neq1}^{P}$
\end_inset

 two for secondary educated,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}_{i_{w}=1}^{S}\text{ and }\hat{h}_{i_{w}\neq1}^{S},$
\end_inset

 and two for tertiary educated,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{h}_{i_{w}=1}^{T}\text{ and }\hat{h}_{i_{w}\neq1}^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

