\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper develops a high-level quantitative framework for studying necessity entrepreneurship as an equilibrium outcome of occupational choice under labor market frictions.
 By defining necessity and opportunity entrepreneurship through counterfactual choices,
 the model separates compositional shifts in entry from changes in aggregate entrepreneurship rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main message is that unemployment risk and social insurance jointly shape who becomes an entrepreneur.
 Reducing insurance can raise entrepreneurship on paper,
 but part of this increase reflects necessity entry associated with lower average firm scale.
 Conversely,
 stronger insurance can reduce necessity entry and improve sorting,
 even when effects on total entrepreneurship are modest.
 These results support evaluating entrepreneurship policy through composition,
 not levels alone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several extensions remain important for the next draft.
 First,
 the credit friction wedge and job-market experiments should be fully completed and integrated into a unified welfare comparison.
 Second,
 calibration choices that are still open should be aligned with the code implementation and reported transparently.
 Third,
 the literature discussion can be broadened further once the project-specific verified PDF library is restored.
\end_layout

